---
import BaseLayout from '@/components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
import Divider from '@/components/ui/Divider.astro';
import Button from '@/components/ui/Button.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About Bay Shine Detailing"
  description="Bay Shine is a solo mobile detailing operation in Pasco County and North Hillsborough, FL. The methodology, the standing-detail philosophy, and the standards behind the work."
>
  <article class="py-24 px-4">
    <div class="container mx-auto max-w-2xl">

      <header class="mb-16">
        <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-4xl sm:text-5xl text-bay-white mb-6 leading-tight">
          About this operation.
        </h1>
        <p class="text-bay-slate text-lg leading-relaxed">
          One technician. One market. No franchises, no employees, no corner-cutting.
        </p>
      </header>

      <Divider class="mb-16" />

      <section class="mb-16 reveal">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-bay-white mb-5">Who runs it and why</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-bay-slate leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Constantine started Bay Shine as a direct response to a market full of operators
            who treat vehicle detailing as a commodity — high volume, low attention, identical
            results regardless of what the vehicle actually needs.
          </p>
          <p>
            The work here runs opposite. Every appointment is a single vehicle. The process
            follows a fixed chemical and mechanical sequence. Nothing is rushed because the
            sequence is the product. A detail done in 90 minutes to hit a volume target is
            not a detail — it's a wash with some spray wax.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mobile was the obvious format. Fewer overheads means the rate stays competitive.
            Working at the client's location means the vehicle doesn't sit in a lot between
            stages. The only thing that matters is the work.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <Divider class="mb-16" />

      <section class="mb-16 reveal">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-bay-white mb-5">The methodology</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-bay-slate leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Every exterior service starts with iron decontamination — a chemical step that
            removes embedded brake dust and ferrous particles from the paint surface before
            any mechanical work touches it. This is non-negotiable. Skipping it and moving
            to clay or polishing grinds contamination into the paint rather than removing it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Synthetic clay comes second. The clay bar step mechanically pulls surface bonded
            contamination that chemistry alone won't remove. It runs panel by panel, in
            sequence, in direct sunlight avoidance — heat causes the lubricant to evaporate
            faster and increases marring risk.
          </p>
          <p>
            Polymer sealant or ceramic coating goes on last, after the surface is clean,
            decontaminated, and — where applicable — paint-corrected. Sealing contaminated
            paint protects the contamination, not the paint. That sequence does not move.
          </p>
          <p>
            Interior work follows a similar logic: compressed air and vacuum before any
            surface contact, which prevents grinding debris into fabric or scratching trim.
            Extraction runs after agitation, not during. Odor treatment is enzymatic —
            bacteria and organic compounds neutralized, not masked.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <Divider class="mb-16" />

      <section class="mb-16 reveal">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-bay-white mb-5">The Standing Detail philosophy</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-bay-slate leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            The recurring program exists because vehicle maintenance is not a one-time event.
            A vehicle detailed once and never maintained degrades back to baseline within
            months. A vehicle detailed on a 6-week cycle stays in a state that's faster to
            restore each visit because contamination doesn't compound between appointments.
          </p>
          <p>
            The economics are straightforward: the first visit is a full reset — full-detail
            time and rate. Every visit after that runs shorter because the baseline is higher.
            The client gets a permanently maintained vehicle. The rate is locked from day one.
            Priority scheduling means the slot is held without competing for availability.
          </p>
          <p>
            Cancel anytime. No contracts. The program earns retention through results, not
            lock-in.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <Divider class="mb-16" />

      <section class="mb-16 reveal">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-bay-white mb-5">For other detailers</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-bay-slate leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            The blog and the Field Guide are written for the industry — technicians and
            operators who want to improve their process, understand the chemistry behind
            what they're using, or get a second opinion on how a specific job should be
            approached.
          </p>
          <p>
            There's no ego in sharing this. Better operators improve the market standard,
            which raises what clients expect, which makes the work more interesting.
            The Field Guide will ship when it's complete — not before.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="reveal">
        <Button href="/contact" variant="primary" class="text-base px-8 py-3.5">
          Book an Appointment
        </Button>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
